h flexible container Don't overfill\tSilicone walls can bulge; keep 2\" below rim FINAL RECOMMENDATION Your Priority\tBest Choice Maximum melt rate (no collapsibility needed)\tMetal can + 1800W immersion = ~50 lbs/hr Collapsible + still functional\tSilicone tub + 1500W immersion = ~40 lbs/hr Most portable (smallest storage)\tSilicone tub folds to 4 inches thick DECISION MATRIX Copy ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │                    WHICH BUILD IS RIGHT FOR YOU?                   │ ├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                    │ │   \"I have storage space, want max performance\"                     │ │         → PROTOTYPE G: Metal Can + 1800W Immersion                 │ │            Cost: ~$185 | Melt: 50 lbs/hr | Storage: 21\"×30\"        │ │                                                                    │ │   \"I need it to collapse for apartment/small space\"                │ │         → PROTOTYPE H: Silicone Tub + 1500W Immersion              │ │            Cost: ~$200 | Melt: 40 lbs/hr | Storage: 20\"×20\"×4\"     │ │                                                                    │ │   \"I want both: collapsible AND max heat\"                          │ │         → Not possible on single circuit without tradeoffs         │ │            Must choose: collapsibility OR maximum wattage          │ │                                                                    │ └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ UPDATED KNOWLEDGE BASE KB ID\tDocument\tStatus KB-009\tPrototype G: Metal Can + Immersion\t✅ Complete KB-010\tMaximum Heat Configurations\t✅ Complete KB-011\tDual-Circuit 3600W System\t✅ Complete KB-012\tPrototype H: Collapsible Silicone Tub\t✅ NEW Want me to find the exact Amazon links for the best-rated 15-gallon silicone tub and 1500W immersion heater with GFCI? is a portable induction cooktop feasible in any scenario to add safe heat source. can i make the metal can an induction ready setup Great question — induction is an elegant, safe heat source. Let me evaluate feasibility. Using Tool | Search portable induction cooktop 1800W outdoor use metal pot heating View Using Tool | Search galvanized steel induction compatible magnetic ferrous metal View Using Tool | Search \"galvanized steel\" magnetic induction heating works OR compatible View Using Tool | Search large induction compatible stock pot 20 quart stainless steel flat bottom View Using Tool | Search heating galvanized steel toxic zinc fumes food safety cooking View This is critical information. Let me now put together a comprehensive answer: INDUCTION COOKTOP FEASIBILITY ANALYSIS THE VERDICT UPFRONT Question\tAnswer\tWhy Can you use induction for snow melting?\t✅ Yes, with the right pot\t1800W induction burners are widely available Will the Behrens galvanized trash can work?\t⚠️ Technically yes, but TOXIC\tGalvanized steel IS magnetic, but releases zinc fumes above 392°F (200°C) Better option?\t✅ Large induction-ready stock pot\tFood-grade stainless steel, no fumes, flat bottom CRITICAL SAFETY WARNING: GALVANIZED STEEL + HEAT Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │                    ⚠️ GALVANIZED STEEL WARNING ⚠️                │ ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                 │ │   ZINC VAPORIZATION BEGINS AT: 392°F (200°C)                   │ │   BOILING WATER:               212°F (100°C)                    │ │                                                                 │ │   ✅ SAFE: Water below boiling (immersion heater, ~180°F)      │ │   ⚠️ RISKY: Steam/splash zones may exceed 200°C locally        │ │   ❌ DANGEROUS: Direct flame or high-heat contact on can walls │ │                                                                 │ │   SYMPTOMS OF ZINC FUME FEVER:                                  │ │   • Flu-like symptoms within 4-10 hours                         │ │   • Fever, chills, muscle aches                                 │ │   • Typically resolves in 24-48 hours                           │ │   • Repeated exposure: cumulative health effects                │ │                                                                 │ │   RECOMMENDATION: Use galvanized ONLY with submerged            │ │   immersion heater (water never boils). For ANY external        │ │   heating method, switch to STAINLESS STEEL.                    │ │                                                                 │ └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ PROTOTYPE I: INDUCTION + STAINLESS STEEL STOCK POT The safest, cleanest heat source option. WHY INDUCTION WORKS FOR THIS Factor\tBenefit No open flame\tZero fire risk Instant on/off\tPrecise control 85-90% efficient\tMore heat to water vs. resistive Portable\tPlug into any 120V outlet Weatherproof potential\tCovered setup possible Dual-use\tCan cook outdoors in summer SHOPPING LIST — INDUCTION BUILD Item\tSpecs\tPrice\tLink Duxtop 1800W Portable Induction Cooktop\t120V/15A, 10 power levels, timer, sensor touch\t~$85–$110\tAmazon - Duxtop 9600LS 20 Qt Stainless Steel Stock Pot (Induction-Ready)\tFlat magnetic bottom, ~5 gallon capacity\t~$50–$70\tAmazon - E-far 20 Qt 12-Gauge Outdoor Extension Cord (25ft)\tHeavy-duty, outdoor-rated\t~$30\tHome Depot Weatherproof Cover/Shelter\tProtect cooktop from snow/rain\t~$20–$40\tTarp + frame or pop-up shelter TOTAL: ~$185–$250 PERFORMANCE COMPARISON: INDUCTION vs IMMERSION Metric\tInduction + Stock Pot\tImmersion Heater + Metal Can Power\t1800W\t1800W Efficiency\t85–90%\t95%+ (direct contact) Effective heat to water\t~1,530W\t~1,710W Max water temp\t212°F (boiling)\t180–200°F (thermostat limited) Capacity\t20 qt (~5 gal)\t31 gal (~8–10 gal usable) Snow melt rate\t~35–45 lbs/hr\t~50 lbs/hr Safety\t✅ No submerged electrical parts\t⚠️ Electrical in water Portability\t✅ Cooktop + pot separate\t⚠️ Heater cord attached Outdoor durability\t⚠️ Cooktop needs protection\t✅ All components outdoor-rated Dual-use value\t✅ Cooking, canning, brewing\t❌ Single-purpose INDUCTION SETUP DIAGRAM Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │              PROTOTYPE I: INDUCTION SNOW MELTER                 │ ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                 │ │                     ❄️ SNOW INPUT ❄️                            │ │                          ↓                                      │ │                   ┌───────────┐                                 │ │                   │  ~~~~~~~~ │  ← 20 Qt Stainless Steel Pot   │ │                   │  ~~~~~~~~ │    (induction-compatible)       │ │                   │  ~~~~~~~~ │    5 gallons hot water          │ │                   └─────┬─────┘                                 │ │                         │                                       │ │                   ┌─────┴─────┐                                 │ │                   │ ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓ │  ← Induction Cooktop (1800W)   │ │                   │ ▓ DUXTOP ▓│    Flat, stable surface         │ │                   │ ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓▓ │                                 │ │                   └─────┬─────┘                                 │ │                         │                                       │ │              ┌──────────┴──────────┐                            │ │              │   12-GAUGE CORD     │                            │ │              │   (to house outlet) │                            │ │              └─────────────────────┘                            │ │                                                                 │ │   WEATHERPROOFING OPTIONS:                                      │ │   • Pop-up canopy over setup                                    │ │   • Plastic storage bin inverted over cooktop when not in use   │ │   • Operating under overhang/carport                            │ │                                                                 │ └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ MAKING THE GALVANIZED CAN \"INDUCTION-READY\" — NOT RECOMMENDED Here's why modifying the Behrens trash can for induction is problematic: Approach\tIssue Use as-is on induction\tGalvanized steel IS magnetic BUT: (1) round bottom won't sit flat; (2) zinc fumes if overheated; (3) induction coil only heats 8–10\" diameter — can is 21\" diameter Weld a flat steel plate to bottom\tDestroys collapsibility; zinc fumes from welding; still only heats small area Place steel plate inside can\tPoor heat transfer; water only heats where plate touches Strip galvanization (acid/grinding)\tExposes bare steel to rust; labor-intensive; voids any warranty Bottom line: It's easier, safer, and cheaper to just buy a proper induction-compatible stock pot. HYBRID APPROACH: INDUCTION + IMMERSION (MAXIMUM HEAT) If you want both heat sources on the same circuit... you can't (1800W induction + 1800W immersion = 3600W = breaker trip). But with two circuits: Config\tCircuit 1\tCircuit 2\tTotal Power\tMelt Rate Dual Induction\t1800W cooktop + pot\t1800W cooktop + pot\t3600W\t~80 lbs/hr Induction + Immersion\t1800W cooktop\t1800W immersion in separate can\t3600W\t~95+ lbs/hr FINAL RECOMMENDATION MATRIX Copy ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │                    WHICH BUILD SHOULD YOU CHOOSE?                      │ ├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                        │ │  PRIORITY: MAXIMUM MELT RATE (single outlet)                           │ │  → PROTOTYPE G: Metal Can + 1800W Immersion                            │ │     ~50 lbs/hr | ~$185 | Simplest setup                                │ │                                                    