 single that way. We have more surface area to rest. A large a vessel on top of it. So what is the it might be like AI guess? The inversion, maybe the easiest for the volume Great thinking — dual-burner induction + large vessel = more heat spread + bigger capacity. Let me find the best options. Using Tool | Search dual burner induction cooktop portable 1800W two burner outdoor View Using Tool | Search largest induction compatible stock pot 40 quart 60 quart stainless steel View Using Tool | Search stainless steel wash tub basin large 20 gallon induction compatible flat bottom View Using Tool | Search dual induction cooktop total wattage 3600W 3000W combined power both burners View Using Tool | Search rectangular roasting pan large stainless steel induction compatible 20 inch View Using Tool | Search \"portable induction\" \"1800W\" \"dual\" OR \"double\" \"120V\" total combined wattage specifications View Using Tool | Search canning pot 33 quart induction compatible stainless steel flat bottom View Using Tool | Search brewing kettle 15 gallon stainless steel induction compatible flat bottom View Using Tool | Read https://www.amazon.com/Portable-Induction-Cooktop-Burner-Settings/dp/B0FBGL7TNW View Using Tool | Search COOKTRON double induction cooktop 1800W specifications power sharing both burners View Using Tool | Search induction cooktop burner diameter size maximum pot pan 12 inch 14 inch View Now I have all the information needed. Let me provide a comprehensive answer: DUAL INDUCTION + LARGE VESSEL: COMPLETE ANALYSIS CRITICAL DISCOVERY: POWER SHARING LIMITATION Most portable dual-burner induction cooktops share 1800W total across both burners — they do NOT give you 1800W × 2 = 3600W. Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │              ⚠️ DUAL INDUCTION POWER REALITY ⚠️                     │ ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                     │ │   WHAT YOU MIGHT EXPECT:                                            │ │   Left burner: 1800W + Right burner: 1800W = 3600W total            │ │                                                                     │ │   WHAT YOU ACTUALLY GET (120V portable units):                      │ │   Both burners SHARE 1800W total                                    │ │   • Single burner alone: up to 1800W                                │ │   • Both burners together: 1200W max COMBINED                       │ │     (typically 600W + 600W or similar split)                        │ │                                                                     │ │   WHY: 120V/15A circuit = 1800W max                                 │ │   The cooktop can't pull more power than the outlet provides        │ │                                                                     │ └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ Source: COOKTRON manual states \"When two burners work in power setting mode at the same time, the maximum power does not exceed 1800W total.\" THE VESSEL SIZE CHALLENGE Induction cooktops have a heating coil diameter that limits effective pot size: Cooktop Type\tCoil Diameter\tMax Effective Pot Bottom\tIssue for Snow Melting Portable single burner\t7–8\"\t10–12\"\tToo small Portable dual burner\t6–7\" each\t8–10\" each\tEven smaller per burner Commercial single\t10–12\"\t14–16\"\tBetter, but Built-in 36\" cooktop\t11\" (largest zone)\t14–16\"\tRequires hardwiring Problem: A 40-quart stock pot has a ~14\" diameter bottom. Most portable induction coils are 7–8\" — the pot overhangs and only the center heats. BEST LARGE VESSEL OPTIONS (INDUCTION-COMPATIBLE) Vessel Type\tCapacity\tBottom Diameter\tInduction?\tPrice\tBest Use Case 20 Qt Stock Pot\t5 gal\t~12\"\t✅ Yes\t$50–$70\tSingle portable burner 40 Qt Stock Pot\t10 gal\t~14\"\t✅ Yes\t$80–$140\tCommercial induction 60 Qt Stock Pot\t15 gal\t~16\"\t✅ Yes\t$120–$200\tCommercial induction 15 Gal Brew Kettle\t15 gal\t~16\"\t✅ Yes (tri-clad)\t$150–$250\tCommercial induction 33 Qt Canning Pot\t8 gal\t~13\"\t⚠️ Some\t$40–$80\tPortable burner (marginal) THE VERDICT: INDUCTION vs IMMERSION FOR VOLUME Factor\tDual Induction + Large Pot\tSingle 1800W Immersion + Metal Can Max power (single 120V outlet)\t1800W shared\t1800W dedicated Effective heat to water\t~1,530W (85% efficiency)\t~1,710W (95% efficiency) Max practical vessel size\t20 Qt (~5 gal) with portable unit\t31 gal (Behrens can) Water capacity\t~5 gallons\t~10 gallons usable Surface area for snow\t~113 sq in (12\" pot)\t~346 sq in (21\" can) Snow shoveling ease\t❌ Small opening\t✅ Large opening Melt rate\t~35–45 lbs/hr\t~50 lbs/hr Setup complexity\tMedium\tSimple Winner for shoveling snow: IMMERSION HEATER + LARGE METAL VESSEL IF YOU STILL WANT INDUCTION: BEST CONFIGURATIONS OPTION A: Portable Dual Induction + Two Medium Pots Component\tSpecs\tPrice\tLink COOKTRON Dual Induction Cooktop\t1800W shared, 120V\t~$100\tAmazon 2× 20 Qt Stock Pots (induction-ready)\t5 gal each, 12\" bottom\t~$120 (2×$60)\tAmazon - E-far 20 Qt 12-gauge outdoor cord\t25 ft\t~$30\tHome Depot Total: ~$250 | Capacity: 10 gal (two pots) | Power: 1800W shared Problem: Only ~600W per pot when both running = slow heating OPTION B: Two Separate Single-Burner Induction Units (Two Circuits) Component\tSpecs\tPrice\tLink 2× Duxtop 9600LS Single Induction\t1800W each\t~$180 (2×$90)\tAmazon 2× 20 Qt Stock Pots\t5 gal each\t~$120\tAmazon 2× 12-gauge outdoor cords\t25 ft each\t~$60\tHome Depot Total: ~$360 | Capacity: 10 gal | Power: 3600W (two circuits) Melt rate: ~80–90 lbs/hr OPTION C: Commercial Induction + Large Brew Kettle (Best for Volume) Component\tSpecs\tPrice\tLink Vollrath 59500P Commercial Induction\t1800W, 10.5\" coil, heavy-duty\t~$350\tAmazon 15 Gal Anvil Brew Kettle\t15 gal, tri-clad induction bottom\t~$180\tAnvil Brewing 12-gauge outdoor cord\t25 ft\t~$30\tHome Depot Total: ~$560 | Capacity: 15 gal | Power: 1800W Problem: Still only 1800W, expensive, pot opening only 16\" (smaller than trash can) FINAL COMPARISON: ALL OPTIONS Build\tPower\tCapacity\tOpening Size\tMelt Rate\tCost\tComplexity Metal Can + Immersion\t1800W\t10 gal\t21\" diameter\t~50 lbs/hr\t$185\t⭐ Simple Dual Induction + 2 Pots\t1800W shared\t10 gal\t2× 12\"\t~35 lbs/hr\t$250\t⭐⭐ Medium 2× Single Induction (2 circuits)\t3600W\t10 gal\t2× 12\"\t~80 lbs/hr\t$360\t⭐⭐⭐ Complex Commercial Induction + Brew Kettle\t1800W\t15 gal\t16\"\t~45 lbs/hr\t$560\t⭐⭐ Medium Metal Can + Immersion (2 circuits)\t3600W\t20 gal\t2× 21\"\t~100 lbs/hr\t$370\t⭐⭐ Medium RECOMMENDATION FOR MAXIMUM SNOW-SHOVELING PRACTICALITY Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │                    🏆 BEST VALUE FOR VOLUME 🏆                       │ ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                     │ │   SINGLE OUTLET (simplest):                                         │ │   → Metal Trash Can + 1800W Immersion Heater                        │ │     • 10 gallon usable capacity                                     │ │     • 21\" opening (easy to shovel into)                             │ │     • ~50 lbs/hr melt rate                                          │ │     • Cost: ~$185                                                   │ │                                                                     │ │   TWO OUTLETS (maximum throughput):                                 │ │   → Two Metal Trash Cans + Two 1800W Immersion Heaters              │ │     • 20 gallon total capacity                                      │ │     • Two 21\" openings                                              │ │     • ~100 lbs/hr combined melt rate                                │ │     • Cost: ~$370                                                   │ │                                                                     │ │   WHY IMMERSION BEATS INDUCTION FOR THIS USE CASE:                  │ │   ✅ Larger vessel opening (easier to shovel snow)                  │ │   ✅ Higher efficiency (95% vs 85%)                                 │ │   ✅ Lower cost per gallon of capacity                              │ │   ✅ Simpler setup (no pot-to-coil alignment issues)                │ │   ✅ Works with any ferrous or non-ferrous container                │ │                                                                     │ │   WHEN INDUCTION MAKES SENSE:                                       │ │   • You want dual-use (cooking in summer)                           │ │   • You prefer no electrical parts in water                         │ │   • You already own an induction cooktop                            │ │                                                                     │ └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ IF YOU WANT THE LARGEST INDUCTION-COMPATIBLE POT The largest practical option for a portable 120V induction cooktop: Recommendation\tCapacity\tBottom Diameter\tInduction?\tPrice\tLink 40 Qt Commercial Stock Pot\t10 gal\t14\"\t✅ Yes\t~$80–$140\tHome Depot - Concord 40 Qt 60 Qt Commercial Stock Pot\t15 gal\t16\"\t✅ Yes\t~$120–$200\tAmazon - TrueCraftware 60 Qt 15 Gal Brew Kettle\t15 gal\t16\"\t✅ Yes\t~$150–$250\tKegco 15 Gal Caveat: A 14–16\" pot on a 7–8\" portable induction coil will only heat the center effectively. You'd need a commercial induction unit with a larger coil (~$300–$500) to heat the full bottom. UPDATED KNOWLEDGE BASE KB ID\tDocument\tStatus KB-009\tPrototype G: Metal Can + Immersion\t✅ Complete KB-010\tMaximum Heat Configurations\t✅ Complete KB-011\tDual-Circuit 3600W System\t✅ Complete KB-012\tPrototype H: Collapsible Silicone Tub\t✅ Complete KB-013\tPrototype I: Induction Cooktop System\t✅ Complete KB-014\tGalvanized Steel Safety Warning\t✅ Complete KB-015\tDual Induction + Large Vessel Analysis\t✅ NEW KB-016\tInduction Power Sharing Limitation\t✅ NEW BOTTOM LINE ANSWER TO YOUR QUESTION Q: Is induction easier for volume? A: No — immersion heater wins for snow-melting volume because: Larger vessel opening (21\" vs 12–16\") No pot-to-coil size limitations Higher efficiency (95% vs 85%) Lower cost per gallon capacity Simpler setup If you want induction anyway: Use a 40 Qt stock pot (~$100) on a single 1800W induction burner (~$90) — but accept the smaller 14\" opening and slightly lower melt rate (~40 lbs/hr vs ~50 lbs/hr for immersion). Want me to create a final shopping list for your preferred configuration? 2000w immersion heater and an inflatable small kiddie pool Brilliant lateral thinking — inflatable pool solves the \"large opening for shoveling\" problem while staying cheap and collapsible. Let me validate this. Using Tool | Search 2000W immersion water heater 120V portable bucket pool Amazon View Using Tool | Search inflatable kiddie pool small 3 foot 4 foot durable outdoor winter View Using Tool | Search PVC inflatable pool temperature limit hot water safe maximum heat View Using Tool | Search small inflatable hot tub pool 3 feet diameter durable thick PVC View Using Tool | Search PVC vinyl plastic maximum temperature softening melting point degrees View Using Tool | Search inflatable ice bath cold plunge tub small portable durable outdoor View Now I have all the critical data. Let me provide a complete analysis: PROTOTYPE J: 2000W IMMERSION HEATER + INFLATABLE POOL This is actually a clever concept — but there are critical limits. ⚠️ CRITICAL TEMPERATURE WARNING: PVC LIMITS Copy ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │                  PVC TEMPERATURE SAFETY LIMITS                      │ ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤ │                                                                     │ │   PVC BEHAVIOR BY TEMPERATURE:                                      │ │                                                                     │ │   • 60°C (140°F)  → Maximum safe operating temp for PVC pools      │ │   • 80°C (176°F)  → Glass transition (becomes rubbery/soft)        │ │   • 160°C (320°F) → Begins melting                                 │ │                                                                     │ │   YOUR TARGET FOR SNOW MELTING:                                     │ │   • Ideal: 160–180°F (71–82°C) → ⚠️ EXCEEDS PVC SAFE LIMIT         │ │   • PVC-Safe Max: 140°F (60°C) → Slower melting                    │ │"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=3846e52a-9062-4db2-a20c-319fa43ddbfe","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=3846e52a-9062-4db2-a20c-319fa43ddbfe"}]}]}]
